# Browserbase Persisted Context (dashboard side)

When a feature needs a workflow to stay logged in across scheduled runs, it needs a
Browserbase **Context**. The dashboard's only job is to provision ONE stable context
and store it; auth reliability is handled runner-side (see below).

## Do this
- Reuse-or-create a **stable** context id per automation. Follow the `ensureBrowserbaseContextId` pattern: reuse `existingAutomation.browserbase_context_id` if present, else `createBrowserbaseContext()`. Never lazily create a new context on each run/save — inconsistent ids silently break persistence (the next run starts logged out).
- Persist it on the `automations` row as `browserbase_context_id` at create/ensure time (see `ensureHospitalityAutomation`). The runner mirrors it to `workflow_browser_contexts`; both must agree.
- Add the new scenario to the same provisioning path so its automation gets a context id too.

## Recorder (`/new`) context is identity-level (company-or-user), frozen on the profile
- The self-serve recorder session (`POST /api/new-automation-sessions`) attaches a persisted context so third-party logins survive. The id is **frozen on `profiles.browserbase_context_id`** the first time it's needed: a corporate user (work-email domain) inherits the **earliest teammate's** context for that domain; a consumer/free-email user gets their own. See `ensureProfileBrowserbaseContextId` in `src/lib/new-automation/recording-context.js`.
- Provision with the **service role** — corporate teammates live in other users' `profiles` rows that per-user RLS hides. Uses the **one** helper (`createBrowserbaseContext`); no separate context table.
- The session runs with `browserSettings.context = { id, persist: true }` (see `createBrowserbaseSession`). On save the same id is stamped onto `automations.browserbase_context_id`, so the runner's `resolve_browserbase_context_id` (per-automation column has precedence) uses it directly and never touches the shared per-scenario `workflow_browser_contexts`.
- **Scope:** only `/new` custom/recorded automations use the identity context. eviivo/gov keep their **dedicated per-scenario** contexts (own reset/pinning lifecycle) — do NOT fold them into the identity jar, or a context reset would wipe every login for that identity.

## Know this
- A Context persists **cookies + localStorage only — NOT sessionStorage**. A freshly created context is an **empty cookie jar**: automated runs will NOT be authenticated until a human completes the first login once via Live View (runner's `scripts/eviivo_login.py`). Build the UX to surface/allow that first login, and don't treat "context created" as "logged in".
- Don't build a second context-creation path or stash the id elsewhere — one helper (`createBrowserbaseContext`), one column (`automations.browserbase_context_id`).

## Reliability lives in the runner (don't reinvent here)
For login-walled sources, IP/fingerprint **pinning**, the **captcha split** (auto-solve on for automated runs, off for manual login), and the **/login → dashboard reload-to-redirect** are all handled in `chromie-runner` / `chromie-tools`. See their `.cursor/rules` (`browserbase-persisted-auth`, `browser-tool-auth-and-scraping`) before assuming a context alone is enough. If the site binds sessions to IP/fingerprint, the context must be paired with runner-side pinning or restored cookies get rejected.
